Monday, 16 Aug 2021 10:32 PM;hopeda;
From: Barouch,Dan (HMFP - Division of Vaccine Research) <dbarouch@bidmc.harvard.edu> 
Sent: Sunday, August 15, 2021 5:30 PM
To: Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C] <debra.hope@nih.gov>; SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>
Cc: Galit Alter <galter@mgh.harvard.edu>
Subject: Re: Published SeroNet data sets-request for data point of contact-Barouch
Can you remind me what the data sharing requirements are for SeroNet?  All the relevant figures are in open access publications.  In many cases, my SeroNet grant only funded a portion of the work in certain publications.
Dan

From: Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C] 
Sent: Monday, August 16, 2021 10:06 PM
To: Barouch,Dan (HMFP - Division of Vaccine Research) <dbarouch@bidmc.harvard.edu>; SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>; Juli Klemm <klemmj@mail.nih.gov>; Samantha (NIH/NCI) Finstad [E] (samantha.finstad@nih.gov) <samantha.finstad@nih.gov>
Cc: Galit Alter <galter@mgh.harvard.edu>
Subject: RE: Published SeroNet data sets-request for data point of contact-Barouch

Dan,
I am looping in the NCI Program team to this thread.    Briefly, the SeroNet data sharing requirements are that the data that supports the findings of a publication must be made publicly available in an open access data repository at the time a manuscript is accepted for publication. 
Your specific comments/questions:
•	While publication in an open access journal is required, it does not fulfill the requirement to make SeroNet data available in an open access data repository.   
•	If a paper acknowledges SeroNet funding,  all of the data in the paper is expected to be made publicly available under this policy.  There may be cases when an exception to this requirement could be requested. A request of this nature would need to undergo review on a case by case basis and exceptions are expected to be rare.

One of the goals  of the Coordinating Center is to make the data sharing process as easy as possible. Once a data POC is identified for each of your papers, we will work with them to receive and review the data as it is prepared for submission to a public  data repository.  
Hope this answers your questions.  For reference, the data sharing requirements can be found in your Terms of Award, your SeroNet Network Agreement and the SeroNet Publication Policy (attached).  
Deb

Sunday, 15 Aug 2021 12:04 AM;hopeda;This paper acknowledged a SeroNet grant but did not use funds to generate the data in the paper.  The PI suggested removing the award acknowledgement (see comments in SPDC-107 for email thread).  This was reviewed with NCI program staff and the Program Director for the grant., who agreed this is the path forward. 


From: "Patriotis, Christos (NIH/NCI) [E]" <patriotisc@mail.nih.gov>
Date: Tuesday, August 10, 2021 at 2:41 PM
To: "Klemm, Juli (NIH/NCI) [E]" <klemmj@mail.nih.gov>
Cc: "Finstad, Samantha (NIH/NCI) [E]" <samantha.finstad@nih.gov>, "Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C]" <debra.hope@nih.gov>
Subject: RE: 

Hi Juli:

Thank you for the e-mail and for getting me up to speed with this. 

Since there has been already a communication between Dr. Cheng and the Coordinating Center on the issue with data sharing and public access, I would prefer if Debra continues the communication with her. From what I see from the e-mail train, Dr. Cheng has already agreed to request the removal of the SeroNet support acknowledgment from this publication since she doesn’t think it would be possible for her to make the data available for public access since it does not belong to her. 

Regards,
Christos



Christos Patriotis, Ph.D.
Program Director



From: Klemm, Juli (NIH/NCI) [E] <klemmj@mail.nih.gov> 
Sent: Saturday, August 7, 2021 1:02 PM
To: Patriotis, Christos (NIH/NCI) [E] <patriotisc@mail.nih.gov>
Cc: Finstad, Samantha (NIH/NCI) [E] <samantha.finstad@nih.gov>; Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C] <debra.hope@nih.gov>
Subject: FW: 

Hi Christos,

Per the thread below, Susan Cheng cited her SeroNet award on a paper for which she’s not able to make the data public. Unfortunately, unless she is able to share the data with the coordinating center to be made public, we’ll need to ask her to remove reference to her SeroNet award (which sounds like it was a relatively small part of the study). We wanted to let you know about this situation and ask if you would prefer to follow up with her. 

Thanks and sorry to send another issue you way!
